January 1996

GENERATION OF TRANSGENIC CASSAVA HAVING REDUCED CYANIDE
TOXICITY

Cassava plants possess a cyanide toxicity that is
harmful to humans.  In fact, a correlation has been
demonstrated between the cyanide content of poorly
processed cassava and the occurrence of the
neurological disorder called Konzo.  This (Ohio State
University) report describes genetic research designed
to develop cassava plants having reduced cyanide
toxicity.  The strategy is to isolate and overexpress
the gene encoding linamarase, the enzyme that converts
linamarin into acetone cyanohydrin.  Most of the
research objectives are achieved, and some are even
expanded upon.  (This 1990 report was only recently
released for public use.)

(Order this LIFE SCIENCES & BIOTECHNOLOGY UPDATE
