<A NAME = "38"></A>Copyright
CHEMICAL BUSINESS NEWSBASE via NewsNet
November 12, 1996

What's in store for Asia?

from CHEMICAL BUSINESS NEWSBASE, 12 Nov 1996

Ref: Asia Pacific Chemicals, Nov 1996, Vol. 7, No. 9, Pg. 15,17

Storage and distribution in Pacific Asia are reviewed.

In some countries in the area the market for plastics is growing 15%
above the growth in GNP.

It is expected that the market for petroleum products will double from
1990 to 2005.

Van Ommeren Tank Terminals (VOTT) serves almost all the Far East, from
Singapore, recently adding India and Pakistan which are no longer
supplied by Russia.

In Singapore it has a 969,000 cu. metre on Pulau Sebarok, working at
almost 100% capacity with 6 M tonnes/y, On Pulau Sakra it has a 66,000
cu. metre terminal which is on long term lease to DuPont for its
adjacent plant.

VOTT also has terminals in China, South Korea, Bangladesh and India.

GATX Terminals has two terminals in Singapore, a joint venture in
China, and is discussing a joint venture in Malaysia.

Stolt NYK Asia-Pacific Services (SNAP) and Stolt-Nielsen Inter Asia
Services (SNIAS) have increased the capacity of their fleet by more
than 45% over the last two years.

SNAP has announced further fleet expansions.

SNIAS is to form a joint venture with Dovechem in China.

