<HR>
<A NAME = "532"></A>Copyright
CHEMICAL BUSINESS NEWSBASE via NewsNet
November 12, 1996

PVC to be recycled as coke alternative

from CHEMICAL BUSINESS NEWSBASE, 12 Nov 1996

Ref: Japan Chemical Week, 24 Oct 1996, Vol. 37, No. 1898, Pg. 7

Within 12 months, new technology allowing waste PVC to be used as a
coke substitute in blast furnaces, is to be made commercially available
by NKK Corp.

The process removes chlorine from the waste as hydrochloric acid,
making it safe for use as a reducing agent in the blast furnace.

At Kawasaki, the company has recently begun operation of a 30,000
tonne/y waste plastic recycling unit at its steel mill.

The waste material is granulated and then used as a reducing agent in
the furnace.

Currently, this system does not recycle PVC or fibre reinforced
plastics.

Copyright 1996 Royal Society of Chemistry




