CHEMICAL BUSINESS NEWSBASE via NewsNet
November 12, 1996

Sony: plastics waste changed into flocculant

from CHEMICAL BUSINESS NEWSBASE, 12 Nov 1996

Ref: Japan Chemical Week, 24 Oct 1996, Vol. 37, No. 1898, Pg. 7

A flocculant suitable for the removal of wastewater pollutants has been
produced from waste polystyrene using new technology developed by Sony
Corp. 13 tonnes of wastewater can be treated with the flocculant
obtained from recycling one PS video cassette.

After use, the flocculant and the pollutants are dehydrated for use in
cement.

The efficiency of the new flocculant is three times that of
polyacrylamide.

