<HR>
<A NAME = "736"></A>Copyright
CHEMICAL BUSINESS NEWSBASE via NewsNet
November 12, 1996

Industry's focus shifting from recycling

from CHEMICAL BUSINESS NEWSBASE, 12 Nov 1996

Ref: Plastics News, 30 Sep 1996, Vol. 8, No. 31, Pg. 8

As public concern shifts away from the problem of solid waste, plastics
companies are turning their attention away from expensive programmes to
recycle plastics to other, more profitable, areas.

At Piscataway, NJ, Union Carbide is to close its HDPE recycling
facility.

Quantum Chemical Co closed a similar unit at Heath, OH, 18 months ago.

On 1 Oct 1996, declining funding from industry will force the closure
of the Center for Plastics Recycling Research, based at Rutgers
University.

The requirement for a minimum recycled content in food packaging in
California, LA, has been dropped from the state's recycling
legislation.

The American Plastics Council is no longer aiming at a 25% recycling
target for rigid bottles and containers.

The plastics industry is now concentrating its efforts on wider
environmentally friendly programmes.

Copyright 1996 Royal Society of Chemistry




<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
